            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Benjamin Cohen was raised on the manicured lawns of Lafayette, a world away from the grit and fog of San Francisco. The only son of a pragmatic tax attorney and a real estate agent, his childhood was a comfortable procession of soccer practices and predictable holidays. Art was a decoration, not a vocation. To please his parents, Ben pursued a Communications degree at UC Davis, a safe choice that promised a stable marketing career. He graduated and dutifully took a job as a marketing coordinator at a fintech startup in San Jose, but the work felt hollow, a slow erasure of his true self.\n\nThe turning point came during a weekend trip to San Francisco. Wandering through the galleries in Hayes Valley, he felt a magnetic pull he hadn't experienced in years. The visceral impact of a bold abstract canvas, the quiet power of a photography exhibit\u2014it was the language he was meant to speak. Within a month, he quit his job, infuriating his father and bewildering his mother.\n\nBen moved into a cramped room in the Outer Richmond and pieced together a living by bussing tables and freelance writing. He spent every spare moment volunteering at galleries, absorbing everything he could. His break came when the owner of a small, avant-garde gallery in Hayes Valley, a sharp-witted woman named Elara, recognized his unflagging passion and intelligence. She offered him the Gallery Assistant position.\n\nThe 0.0-mile commute is no exaggeration; Ben lives in a small converted loft above the gallery, a perk that makes his modest salary viable. His daily routine is an immersion in art. He wakes to the smell of curing paint, spends his days handling artwork, corresponding with artists, and engaging with patrons. His social life revolves around a tight-knit group of fellow creatives\u2014a musician, a poet, and a graphic designer\u2014who meet for cheap beer and ambitious conversations.\n\nBen's dream is to become a curator, to have his own vision shape a gallery space and launch the careers of undiscovered artists. He feels an intense connection to San Francisco, not for its tech boom, but for its legacy of counter-culture and artistic rebellion. For Ben, living above the gallery isn't just a living arrangement; it's a total commitment to a life he chose for himself, one masterpiece at a time."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the heat in his face, standing before a chaotic abstract canvas in Hayes Valley. It was all violent slashes of crimson and deep, consuming indigo. The gallery was quiet, but the painting screamed with a raw honesty that countered the polite hedges of his childhood. In that moment, the sterile path his parents celebrated simply dissolved. It wasn\u2019t a choice to leave his old life anymore; it was a rescue. He felt truly seen for the first time, not by a person, but by a truth rendered in paint.\n\n2.\nA year before the loft, the fog in his Outer Richmond room was so thick he could taste it. He ate instant noodles straight from the pot, his fingers numb from a double shift bussing tables. On his lap was a worn library book on the Gutai art movement. The exhaustion was a heavy blanket, but underneath it was a spark of defiant joy. This cold, hungry-artist clich\u00e9 felt infinitely more authentic than any catered lunch at his old fintech job. He knew then that this struggle was building something real.\n\n3.\nHe was sweeping up confetti after a chaotic opening he\u2019d volunteered for when Elara cornered him. \u201cThat couple,\u201d she said, nodding toward the door, \u201cyou didn\u2019t just sell them a piece, you gave them a story about it.\u201d Ben froze, remembering how he\u2019d connected the artist's biography to their own. Her sharp eyes held no pity, only assessment. \u201cThe upstairs loft is empty. The keys are yours if you start Monday.\u201d It felt less like a job offer and more like an invitation into the life he\u2019d been dreaming of.\n\n4.\nLast fall, squeezed into a booth at a dive bar with his friends. The group\u2019s poet, Maya, read a new verse from her phone, its rhythm fighting the jukebox. Their friend Leo, a graphic designer, sketched a logo on a napkin, inspired by her words. Ben found himself passionately defending a difficult installation piece they\u2019d all seen. A profound sense of belonging washed over him. This was his corner of the universe, a place where ideas, not stock options, were the currency. He was finally with his people.\n\n5.\nLate one Tuesday, unpacking a new shipment, he placed a stark, minimalist sculpture next to a frenetic, colorful photograph just to get it out of the way. He stepped back and gasped. The cold steel of the sculpture seemed to silence the photograph\u2019s visual noise, creating an entirely new conversation between them about stillness and chaos. No one had told him to do it; the vision was entirely his. In that silent, electric moment, the vague dream of becoming a curator became a burning, tangible goal."
        },
